---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/withBase.js";
---

<Base
  title="How GlassBox stays honest"
  description="What the tracer proves, what it doesn't, and how the build enforces the difference."
>
  <h1>How GlassBox stays honest</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    GlassBox's whole premise is that you can trust what you see. So it draws a hard line between what the
    machine produced and what a human claimed — in the data, in the build, and on every lesson.
  </p>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What the tracer proves</h2>
    <p>
      Each lesson is a real Python program. At build time it runs under CPython's
      own <code>sys.settrace</code>, and the variable state shown at every line is exactly what the
      interpreter held at that moment. It is not a mock-up, an animation, or a teacher's recollection — it
      is execution output. A hand-drawn slide can lie about what a variable holds; a real execution trace
      cannot. Traces of this kind are marked:
    </p>
    <p><span class="badge derived"><span class="led"></span>execution-derived · CPython</span></p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>What it does not prove</h2>
    <p>
      The metaphors (two cups), the problem statements, and the step notes are <em>human pedagogy</em> laid
      on top of the trace. A note like “the spare cup saved the day” is a claim about meaning, not a fact
      the interpreter produced. The player always shows notes in a distinct register so prose can never
      masquerade as execution output. Where a whole lesson models a process by hand rather than tracing
      real code, it is marked:
    </p>
    <p><span class="badge asserted"><span class="led"></span>author-asserted</span></p>
    <p class="muted">Every lesson in this portal is currently execution-derived.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="card">
    <h2>The build enforces it</h2>
    <p>
      Lessons live in one place; traces are generated by the tracer into another and are the only thing the
      player reads — the two are never mixed at authoring time. Before anything ships, the build gate
      validates every trace against a single schema and <strong>fails loud</strong> if a trace's claim of
      being execution-derived doesn't match how it was produced. A second gate keeps the material
      provider-agnostic. Nothing ships unvalidated.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      GlassBox is AI-authored under an owner-designed verification system: the verification system — not a
      human checking every line — is the safeguard, and the build fails when a claim doesn't hold.
    </p>
  </section>

  <p class="back"><a href={withBase("/lessons/swap/")}>← Back to the swap lesson</a></p>
</Base>

<style>
  .card { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .card h2 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.15rem; }
  .muted { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; }
  .back { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
</style>
